\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
On one hand, status goods are a meant to indicate a consumer's exclusive
 status while on the other, they are also meant to create bandwagons for
 those with lower status.
 To understand this supposed universal race to exclusivity, status consumption
 has been often associated with the consumer's reference group.
 Without that, it is difficult to understand how the not-so-rich are observed
 to spend disproportionately higher on status items while the high-status
 individuals also spend more on status goods.
 Where all consumers are supposed to benefit from higher status consumption,
 reference groups help us pin down a certain level of status consumption
 as the consumers' social need.
 In empirical terms, they help clarify whether a given status item is more
 valuable to those who already have higher 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

status
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or to those who don't (e.g.
 by asking whether the consumers belong to the same reference group or not).
 Unlike the mechanisms of invidious comparison (IC) and pecuniary emulation
 (PE) identified by Veblen - concerns that are essentially normative - reference
 groups provide a descriptive context for status competitions where a consumer
 may identify her status.
 This is important - since the consumer's social need for status items is
 hardly as universal as for essential food or clothing.
 Since social needs are determined by the consumer's interaction with others
 in the economy, the demand for status items necessarily depends on social
 participation and exclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-transactional environments of consumer choice and the uncertainty
 inherent in perception of status have already been explored in the literature
 on status consumption - most particularly by Cole-Maliath and Hopkins-Kornienko.
 In the proposed chapter, we extend rely on this framework to explore consumer
 choice under extreme income inequalities and take an approach similar to
 Cole-Maliath in assuming that consumer does not obtain utility directly
 from the reference but through variables in her utility that are shaped
 by her reference.
 We focus in particular on the uncertainty arising out of non-transactional
 choices that contribute to the consumer's future expectations from status
 competitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The core of our argument is that if status goods - such as jewelry or a
 club membership - offered returns towards status that are not any more
 uncertain than the purchase of expensive long-term assets such as a house
 or a private jet, the representative consumer would know of the futility
 of status consumption (compared to saving towards higher wealth).
 The substitution between saving and consumption in the intertemporal substituti
on framework is therefore not suitable for understanding status consumption
 unless one considers either i) that the consumer's utility is subject to
 the risk implied by status consumption or ii) that the status items offer
 a utility different from the one that is derived from regular goods.
 While the latter option of splitting utility into visible and non-visible
 terms has its advantages, we find that the distinctions between items or
 status and regular utility may be more difficult to justify empirically
 under environments of extreme income inequalities (e.g.
 in developing economies where relative wealth is more easily visible).
 This motivates the proposed approach to viewing status consumption as the
 consumer's risky position in an intertemporal framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is similar to the approach followed by Hopkins-Kornienko who explore
 status competitions for a given distribution of success-determining attributes
 in a population of consumers.
 It is worth emphasising that the inequality in rewards is considered different
 from inequality in incomes - a distinction that we also make for our specific
 instance of persistent (long-term) income inequalities caused due to geographic
, occupational or social differences.
 With near permanent income inequalities, the consumer's hope to overcome
 the persistent inequality coincides with the promise of status competitions
 where status consumption is rewarded.
 In an approach similar to Cole-Maliath, we use a finite set of income bands
 and the transition probabilities among them determine the future wealth
 states of the consumer and her expectations towards the future.
 The basic needs of the consumer are supposed to be already met in this
 economy so that the only option she faces is to either save towards future
 assets or spend her income above needs towards status consumption.
 The fundamental assumption for the transition probability is that it encompasse
s all possible paths which a consumer could follow rise in the hierarchy
 of income.
 The utility from future wealth thus consists both of the current value
 of assets and the probability of being in the same or different income-bands
 in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, the probabilities that define the transition to successive income
 bands is assumed to be the same for all consumers within an income band.
 As consumers discover their success only through performance in the status
 competitions, the preferences and attributes of the consumers in an income
 band remain unchanged as consumers transition across bands.
 If the population of consumers in the income bands does not change over
 time, the processes of accumulation and inheritance would ensure on one
 hand that the assets acquired by consumers in various income bands would
 grow apart over time, but on the other that a certain mobility for all
 participants in the economy is permitted through status competitions to
 assist inclusion, fairness and stability among the bands.
 In other words the consumers in the higher income-band with the higher
 income maintain a competition to admit those below the respective band
 to become a member.
\end_layout

