\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[SC - random] The presence of status competitions allow the income inequalities
 to prevail.
 If the preferences for all consumers are the same, an equilibrium is implied
 in an economy with different bands of disposable incomes if the consumers
 can move across bands for a certain cost.
 Since long-term inequalities in income are persistent through the long-term
 equilibrium, the status competitions which the consumers participate in
 must be population-preserving in the sense that in the long-run the number
 of consumers who leave the an income band must be balanced by those who
 enter the income band.
 The long-term income inequalities cannot exist if not for such a population
 preserving status competition.
 What such a population preserving competition implies is a scheme where
 into two successive bands are swapped with each other over time.
 The presence of status consumption implies the possibilty that the richer
 band would spend poportionately higher on status competitions and the long-term
 equilibrium would sustain income inequalities across the bands as well
 as the status competitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To elaborate this further, notice that the final state of the consumers
 wouldn't be any difference from with the swapping mechanism if they incurred
 no cost for status consumption.
 If however, a swap of consumers from two successive bands is at a certain
